05254nam a22008055i 9780813561196DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2013    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135611967 a10.36019/97808135611962doi  a(DE-B1597)526124  a(OCoLC)859537489  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0000002bisacsh  aHU 17272rvk1 aSocolovsky, Maya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aTroubling Nationhood in U.S. Latina Literature :bExplorations of Place and Belonging /cMaya Socolovsky. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatinidad: Transnational Cultures in the00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Troubling America(s) -- t1. Spaces of the Southwest: Dis-ease, Disease, and Healing in Denise Chávez's The Last of the Menu Girls and Face of an Angel -- t2. Mestizaje in the Midwest: Remapping National Identity in the American Heartland in Ana Castillo's Sapogonia and Sandra Cisneros's Caramelo -- t3. Colonization and Transgression in Puerto Rican Spaces: Judith Ortiz Cofer's The Line of the Sun and The Meaning of Consuelo -- t4. Memoirs of Resistance: Colonialism and Transnationalism in Esmeralda Santiago's When I Was Puerto Rican, Almost a Woman, and The Turkish Lover -- t5. Tales of the Unexpected: Cuban American Narratives of Place and Body in Himilce Novas's Princess Papaya -- tPostscript. The Illegal Aliens of American Letters: Troubling the Immigration Debate -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book examines the ways in which recent U.S. Latina literature challenges popular definitions of nationhood and national identity. It explores a group of feminist texts that are representative of the U.S. Latina literary boom of the 1980s, 1990s, and 2000s, when an emerging group of writers gained prominence in mainstream and academic circles. Through close readings of select contemporary Mexican American, Puerto Rican, and Cuban American works, Maya Socolovsky argues that these narratives are "remapping" the United States so that it is fully integrated within a larger, hemispheric Americas. Looking at such concerns as nation, place, trauma, and storytelling, writers Denise Chavez, Sandra Cisneros, Esmeralda Santiago, Ana Castillo, Himilce Novas, and Judith Ortiz Cofer challenge popular views of Latino cultural "unbelonging" and make strong cases for the legitimate presence of Latinas/os within the United States. In this way, they also counter much of today's anti-immigration rhetoric. Imagining the U.S. as part of a broader "Americas," these writings trouble imperialist notions of nationhood, in which political borders and a long history of intervention and colonization beyond those borders have come to shape and determine the dominant culture's writing and the defining of all Latinos as "other" to the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aAmerican literaturexHispanic American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aBelonging (Social psychology). 0aHispanic American womenxIntellectual life. 0aHispanic Americans in literature. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in literature. 0aNational characteristics, Latin American, in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813561196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.